The Toca Juparanã cave is a granitic talus cave that was formed by water removal of smaller sediments between large collapsed granitic blocks. The cave has two entrances of irregular shape, delineated by the contact of boulders (

). The main chamber of the cave has an irregular floor made up of collapsed boulders (

) and is euphotic/disphotic due to the presence of two entrances located on either side of the chamber. There is a descending aphotic conduit from this chamber, which is crossed by a small hypogenic drainage. Specimens of 

C. jequitinhonha
Cardoso & Ferreira

, 
n. sp.
were found under fallen rocks in this conduit trespassed by the small drainage, although the specimens were not observed close to the mainstream passage. The only visible organic resource in this area was plant debris brought by water, indicating that the isopods were likely feeding on this resource (

).

